<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="1001" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1001">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 703.4112/7.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">British Ambassador</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-09">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 9, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: I beg to acknowledge
                            the receipt of your personal note of the 1st instant, in which, with
                            reference to your note of the 30th ultimo, you advise the Department
                            that, on April 29 last, Sir Lionel Garden had turned over to the
                            Brazilian Minister at Mexico City the charge of American interests.</p>
                        <p>In reply I beg to ask that you will be so good as to convey to Sir Lionel
                            Carden an expression of this Government’s thanks for his services in
                            this matter.</p>
                        <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>